{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586763"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:39:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15099"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15099"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.03,0.8,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7787"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67288"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7065"},{"type":"tags","id":"10569"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27964"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He exercises regularly and cycles to work. He does not smoke and drinks several glasses of wine at weekends. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The General Practitioner suggests that prostate cancer screening with measurement of prostate specific antigen (PSA) might be appropriate. The patient is cautioned that the PSA might be transiently elevated with certain activities. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following activities can cause a transient elevation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alcohol consumption","Eating a high-fat meal","Ejaculation","Swimming","Walking"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral activities and conditions can affect PSA levels, and understanding these factors is crucial for accurate interpretation of PSA test results. \u003Cstrong\u003EEjaculation\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a transient elevation in PSA levels that may persist for 48-72 hours. This occurs due to the mechanical manipulation of the prostate gland during sexual activity and the release of prostatic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWalking\u003C/strong\u003E is a low-impact exercise that does not significantly affect PSA levels. Normal daily activities like walking do not cause mechanical stimulation of the prostate gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwimming\u003C/strong\u003E, while being a form of exercise, typically does not cause significant PSA elevation as it is a non-impact activity that does not put pressure on the prostate gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEating a high-fat meal\u003C/strong\u003E does not directly affect PSA levels. While diet may have long-term effects on prostate health, it does not cause acute changes in PSA measurements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol consumption\u003C/strong\u003E does not cause significant acute changes in PSA levels. While chronic heavy alcohol use may affect overall prostate health, it does not cause transient PSA elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther factors that can affect PSA levels include digital rectal examination (elevation for 24-48 hours), vigorous exercise particularly cycling (temporary elevation), and prostate infection or inflammation. For accurate PSA testing, it is recommended to avoid ejaculation for 48 hours before the test and to inform the healthcare provider about recent prostate manipulation or vigorous exercise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["PSA levels can be transiently elevated for 48-72 hours following ejaculation.","Digital rectal examination can cause PSA elevation for 24-48 hours.","Vigorous exercise, particularly cycling, can temporarily increase PSA levels."],"references":["Rajaei M, Momeni A, Kheiri S, Ghaheri H. Effect of ejaculation on serum prostate specific antigen level in screening and non-screening population. J Res Med Sci. 2013 May;18(5):387-90. PMID: 24174942; PMCID: PMC3810571.","David MK, Leslie SW. Prostate-Specific Antigen. [Updated 2024 Sep 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557495/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67288"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15099"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67288"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T20:47:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T20:53:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7787"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position"